{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17605623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17605623"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:03:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:03:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15869"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15869","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15869"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8560"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63139"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8560"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15869"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48590"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"8727"},{"type":"tags","id":"8728"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20531"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20618"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63139"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring embryological development, surface ectoderm adjacent to the optic vesicle thickens, going on to form the lens placode.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the next sequence of events in eye development?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The optic cup forms first, then induces the lens placode to form the lens vesicle","The lens placode invaginates to form the lens vesicle, inducing formation of the optic cup","The optic vesicle degenerates and is replaced by the lens placode","The lens placode flattens and disperses into mesenchymal tissue","The lens vesicle and optic cup form simultaneously without induction"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct sequence in eye development involves the \u003Cstrong\u003Elens placode invaginating to form the lens vesicle, which then induces the formation of the optic cup\u003C/strong\u003E. This inductive interaction is crucial for proper eye development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent common misconceptions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoptic cup forming first and inducing lens formation\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - the lens placode actually induces optic cup formation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimultaneous formation without induction\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - inductive interactions are essential\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoptic vesicle degeneration\u003C/strong\u003E does not occur - it transforms into the optic cup\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elens placode flattening and dispersing\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - it invaginates to form the lens vesicle\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe optic cup formation creates two layers: the inner layer becomes the neural retina, while the outer layer becomes the retinal pigment epithelium.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The optic cup forms from invagination of the optic vesicle during week 5 of development","The lens placode forms from surface ectoderm and induces formation of the optic cup","The inner layer of the optic cup becomes the neural retina while the outer layer becomes the retinal pigment epithelium"],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015.","Ludwig PE, Lopez MJ, Czyz CN. Embryology, Eye Malformations. In: StatPearls [Online]. [U